=== Lesson 27-2 (Step-by-Step Approach) ===

 {"type":"h3","text":"Step-by-Step Approach"}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Step 1: Locate the Principle in the Passage"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"The question stem will almost always direct you to a specific idea..."}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Step 2: Isolate the Principle and Its Conditions"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Don't just read the principle—dissect it. Your goal is to create a simple checklist..."}
 {"type":"list","items":["**Example:** If the passage defines a specific type of legal fraud as \"an intentional misrepresentation of a material fact,\" your checklist would be:\n1. Was there a misrepresentation?\n2. Was it intentional?\n3. Was the fact material?"]}

{ "type": "diff-note", "text": "The legal fraud checklist example is the module's best teaching moment. It makes the abstract 'create a checklist' instruction concrete and memorable.", "variant": "comment" }

 {"type":"h4","text":"Step 3: Apply the Checklist to Each Answer Choice"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Treat each answer choice as a separate case study...If a scenario fails even one condition, eliminate it immediately."}
+{{+**Try this:** Attempt the question before reading the analysis below.+}}
+{{+Add a worked example here showing the checklist applied to 3 answer choices: one passing all conditions (correct), one failing one condition, and one that introduces an extra condition not in the principle.+}}
 {"type":"hr"}
 {"type":"h3","text":"If You Get Stuck Between Two Choices..."}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Tie-Breaker #1: The Strict Re-Check"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"...Go back to the passage and re-read the sentence(s) describing the rule, paying extremely close attention to every word..."}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Tie-Breaker #2: Focus on the Difference"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"...ask, \"What is the single key difference between these two answer choices?\"..."}
